create-widget:file-sharer
  parent:content
  class:col-xs-12
  style:""min-height:500px;""
  widgets
    text:@""<p class=""""col-xs-9"""">Welcome to the file sharer example. This example demonstrates how you could create a file sharing service
for your business, to allow your employees to upload and download documents of graded nature. To upload documents
and files, simply drag and drop them from your desktop to your browser. The files uploaded this way, will be stored
in the folder """"/common/private/"""", which means that they will not be accessible, for anyone being a 
<em>""""guest""""</em> on your website. This means
that if you run this example on a web server, that have exclusively allowed https, then you can safely
share whatever files you wish, without having unaothorized personel being able to spy on what data you and your employees 
are sharing with each other.</p>
<p class=""""col-xs-9"""">This example also serves as a <em>""""WikiLeaks Drop Box""""</em>, which allows users to anonymously drop 
off files to your server, without compromising their identity. This feature requires usage of Tor Browser, which the user 
will be warned about, if he tries to access the site anonymously. If you wish to use the example as such, then simply change its 
""""Access Role"""" to """"No restrictions"""". However, by default, any registered user can view, and download, any files dropped
off here, but only <em>""""root""""</em> can delete files.</p>
<p class=""""col-xs-9"""">To avoid files overwiting each other, any new files dropped here, will be prefixed with a random Guid. After revising
the file, you might want to rename the file, and remove this prefix using e.g. the <em>""""superuser/Files""""</em> menu item
as an administrator or superuser.</p>""

    /*
